[test-file.xlsx](https://github.com/exceljs/exceljs/files/4554933/test-file.xlsx)

I solved the problem. Hope this helps you.
If you download this excel file from the server side (In my case Node JS). 
The problem is solved by one line on the client side:  **req.responseType = "arraybuffer";**

```
requestData(req, "exportToExcel")
            .then(resXHR => {
                // For the correct processing of data from the server, you must specify the format/structure of data transfer
                resXHR.responseType = "arraybuffer"
                // Wait until the data is downloaded from the server
                resXHR.onload = function () {
                    // Call a modal window for saving with type and file name 
                    saveAs(new Blob([resXHR.response], { type: 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet' }), 'users.xlsx')
                }
            })
```

Facing the same issue when I'm trying to edit an existing excel sheet, to fix this I've done all the updates on the existing workbook and before sending the response/uploading I'm creating another workbook and looping all the sheets, rows and cell and adding the respective data and styles from the old workbook.

```
  let newWorkbook = new Excel.Workbook();
    oldWorkbook.eachSheet(function(worksheet: any) {
      let newSheet = newWorkbook.addWorksheet(worksheet.name);
      worksheet.eachRow(function(row: any) {
          newSheet.addRow(row.values)
      })
   })
```
This is for sure not the optimal way of fixing but can help you in getting unblocked, please do mind to add your row styles or cell styles while iterating to elements.

If we think about having a standard function that can take care of all this? I'll try to come up with one if anybody needs it.

Faced the same issue. Find out it was because I copied a model of a different worksheet (blueprint) and by doing this the name of the worksheet (sheet) didn't match anymore with the name I created, resetting the name to the original one fixed it for me!
`
var sheet = wb.addWorksheet(originalName);

 sheet.model = Object.assign(blueprintSheet.model,
      {mergeCells: blueprintSheet.model.merges});

  sheet.name = orginialName;
`

I hope this helps anyone!

